com.ibm.xmi.framework
Interface Data

All Known Subinterfaces:
AssociationEnd, Attribute, AttributeValue, Classifier, Contained, Container, Datatype, DataValue, Enum, EnumValue, Extension, Feature, LinkEnd, ObjectValue, Package, Reference, Value, XMIClass, XMIObject, XMLElement
All Known Implementing Classes:
DataImpl
public interface Data

This interface is the root interface for the interface hierarchy representing XMI data. The purpose of this hierarchy is to represent a simple object model that is a subset of OMG MOF and UML that represents the state of objects, the structural features of classes, packages, and XMI extensions. By using the constructs of this object model, you can represent the state of objects that will be saved in XMI files and the structural features of classes and packages that are put in XMI DTDs.

XMIObjects represent instances of classes. They consist of values and XMI extensions. Framework values correspond to UML attribute links (UML's way of representing attributes of instances of classes) and to UML link ends.

The XMIClass in the framework represents classes. Classes also have features; the features in classes define the legal values of instances of the class.

Framework packages are containers that can contain other packages and classes.

This documentation uses the word 'construct' to refer to a part of the framework object model that implements the Data hierarchy.

Each of these constructs is described in further detail in the javadocs for the interface corresponding to the construct.

Each construct has sets of tag values; previously, only XMIObjects had sets of tag values.

Each construct in the data hierarchy has the following characteristics:

  • XMI name -- used to store the construct in an XMI file
  • Namespace -- used to store the construct in XMI 1.1 and XMI 2.0 files
  • XMI file -- the file the construct was loaded from
  • Owner -- the construct that owns this construct
  • Definer -- the construct that defines this construct
  • Defined -- the constructs that are defined by this construct
  • Derived -- the construct derived from this construct
  • Source -- the construct from which this construct was derived

The methods in this class contain the letters XMI to help avoid conflicts with methods in classes generated by the UML2Java class.

Returns:
Collection An empty or unmodifiable collection of constructs that implement the Data interface

getXMIDefiner

public Data getXMIDefiner()
Framework objects and values have definers that specify legal characteristics for them. Here is a table of constructs and their definers:

Construct Definer
XMIObject The corresponding XMIClass
Value of an object The corresponding feature of a class

For example, an XMIClass defines what values can legally be added to XMIObjects that represent instances of the class.

If you use a workspace when you load an XMI file, the objects and values are connected to their definers. See the Workspace class documentation for more details.

The definer may be null.

Returns:
The definer for this data

getXMIDerived

public Data getXMIDerived()
By deriving constructs from other constructs, you can represent associations between "meta" levels if you are working with something like the OMG MOF four layer metamodel architecture.

The framework sets this property for XMIObjects from XMI files that represent UML 1.1 models. For more details, please see the documentation for the DeclarationFactory class.

This method may return null.

Returns:
The construct derived from this construct

getXMIFile

public XMIFile getXMIFile()
If a construct was created by the framework when loading an XMI file, the XMI file for the construct is set. If you create a construct, this method will return null.
Returns:
The XMI file for this data, or null.

getXMINamespace

public Namespace getXMINamespace()
XMI 1.1 and 2.0 lets you use XML namespaces in your XMI files, DTDs, and schemas. The framework ignores namespaces if you are working with XMI 1.0.

If there is a definer for this construct, the namespace for the definer is returned. The namespace can be null.

Returns:
The namespace for the data

getXMIName

public java.lang.String getXMIName()
Each construct has an XMI name except for XMI extensions. This name is used to represent the construct in XML files, so the names must be legal XML tag names and XML attribute names. It is your responsibility to assign a legal XMI name for each construct.

XML allows letters, numbers, "-" and "." characters in names, but not many other characters.

If there is a namespace for this construct, the XMI name is the namespace name followed by ":" and the name of the construct, unless the namespace name is null or "".

Please see the document "XMI Application Framework" for a detailed discussion of how to set the XMI names for various constructs. If you use classes generated by the framework, the XMI names for constructs are set for you so you do not need to do it yourself. Please see the UML2Java class documentation for more details.

The framework gets the XMI name from the definer if one is set for this construct.

Returns:
The XMI name for this construct.

getXMIOwner

public Data getXMIOwner()
Constructs may have owners. The legal owners of constructs are as follows:

Construct Owner
XMIObject Extension
XMIClass Package
Package Package
Feature of a class The class the feature belongs to
Value of an object The object the value belongs to
XMLElement Extension

The framework automatically sets owners when you add constructs to other constructs. For example, if you add a class to a package, the framework sets the owner of the class to the package.

The owner may be null.

Returns:
The owner of the construct

getXMISource

public Data getXMISource()
The construct from which this construct was derived. You can use this along with the derived property to represent relationships between "meta" levels in a metamodel architecture like that of OMG MOF.

The framework sets this property for constructs created by the DeclarationFactory from UML models. See the DeclarationFactory class documentation for more details.

The source may be null.

Returns:
The source construct from which this construct was derived

setXMIDefiner

public void setXMIDefiner(Data d)
                   throws XMIException
Set the definer for this construct. See the getXMIDefiner method documentation details about which constructs can have definers, and what those definers can be. If you attempt to assign a definer of the wrong type to this construct, a BadDefinerException is thrown.

For example, if this construct is an XMIObject, and you attempt to set its definer to a feature, a BadDefinerException is thrown.

Parameters:
d - The definer for this construct
Throws:
BadDefinerException - If the definer is the wrong kind
